properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A deepening Pacific low will make its way across Washington state on Monday. Abundant moisture associated with the system combined with cold air to the north of its trajectory will produce heavy snowfall across the southern interior of British Columbia. Snow will begin Monday morning and intensify Monday evening. It will taper off by Tuesday morning. Snowfall amounts will range from 25 to 35 cm. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions expected near the Richardson Mountains. A weak weather disturbance moving into central Yukon will generate east winds of 70 km/h gusting to 90 near the Richardson Mountains today. These strong winds will cause poor visibility in blowing snow and wind chill values down to minus 50. Winds are forecast to diminish this afternoon. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Road closures are possible. properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: 30-50 cm of snow is expected by Tuesday evening in southwestern Alberta. For the City of Calgary 20-25 cm of snow is expected by the end of the day on Tuesday. A strong low pressure system will develop in Montana Monday afternoon. This low will bring heavy snow to southwestern Alberta, including Banff National Park, beginning Monday afternoon. Snow is expected to persist throughout the day on Tuesday. Easterly upslope winds will enhance the snowfall along the terrain with locally more than 50 cm possible. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Atmospheric conditions could result in a deterioration in air quality. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. In Quebec, wood heating is the main source of fine particles that contribute to smog during winter. This activity generates the largest number of these particulates, more than industrial activities and transportation. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canada’s website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministère de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montréal, visit the Réseau de surveillance de la qualité de l’air de la Ville de Montréal’s website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Québec, visit the Ministère de la Santé et des Services sociaux’s website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction régionale de santé publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-l’Île-de-Montréal at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall and strong winds are expected Monday night into Tuesday. Total rainfall: 25 to 40 mm. Maximum wind gusts: likely exceeding 90 km/h on Tuesday. Locations: Iles de la Madeleine Time span: beginning Monday night and continuing into Tuesday. Remarks: Rain is expected to begin Monday evening over the island and will become heavy at times overnight before tapering to showers or flurries late in the day on Tuesday. In addition, strong east to northeast winds will develop across the island Monday night, then shift to very strong and gusty westerly winds on Tuesday. At this time, the strong gusts are likely to be over 90 km/h. Wind warnings may be issued as this weather event draws nearer. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
